  "response_text": "The Pythagorean theorem is a fundamental concept in geometry that describes the relationship between the lengths of the sides of a right-angled triangle. It states that:\n\n**a\u00b2 + b\u00b2 = c\u00b2**\n\nwhere a and b are the lengths of the two sides that form the right angle (the legs of the triangle), and c is the length of the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle).\n\n**Intuitive Understanding:**\n\nBefore diving into the proof, let's explore the intuition behind the theorem. Imagine a right-angled triangle with legs of length a and b, and a hypotenuse of length c. If we were to draw a square on each side of the triangle, we would have three squares: one on each leg and one on the hypotenuse.\n\nIf we add the areas of the two squares on the legs, we would get a\u00b2 + b\u00b2. Now, if we were to draw a square on the hypotenuse, its area would be",
